-- America Movil, Grupo Bimbo, Petrobras, Pao de Acucar: Latin Equity Preview
-- Alexander Ragir
-- 2010-06-24T03:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-24/america-movil-grupo-bimbo-petrobras-pao-de-acucar-latin-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Latin American trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous
close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  dropped 1.1 percent to
3,883.71. In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-
traded class of stock.  
 Brazil  
 Cia. Brasileira de Distribuicao Grupo Pao de Acucar  (PCAR5
BS): Maquina de Vendas SA, Brazil’s second-biggest retailer
created by a merger this year, agreed to buy electrical-
appliances chain City Lar, increasing the number of its stores
to 750. Pao de Acucar, Brazil’s biggest retailer, rose 0.9
percent to 62.76 reais.  
 Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BS): Brazil’s state-
controlled oil company said its seventh well in the offshore
Tupi field confirmed the potential of light oil in pre-salt
reserves. The 3-BRSA-821-RJS well, known as Tupi Alto, is about
275 kilometers (170 miles) off the coast of Rio de Janeiro
state, Petrobras said in a regulatory filing. It also said
separately it obtained a credit line of as much as $1 billion
from the Agency of Credit and Exportation of Norway, known as
GIEK. The stock fell 2.1 percent to 28.50 reais.  
 Mexico  
 America Movil SAB  (AMXL MM): Billionaire  Carlos Slim , who
controls the largest wireless carrier in Latin America, said the
telecommunications industry still has “a lot of area to grow”
as more people seek Internet services over landline and wireless
connections. The stock rose 2.6 percent to 32.33 pesos.  
 Grupo Bimbo SAB  (BIMBOA MM): The world’s largest bread
maker sold $800 million of 10-year bonds in its first
international issue. The 4.875 percent notes due in 2020 priced
to yield 4.91 percent, or 180 basis points more than similar-
maturity U.S. Treasuries, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point. Bank of
America Corp., Barclays Plc and HSBC Holdings Plc arranged the
sale. Bimbo climbed 0.7 percent to 97.86 pesos.  
